Running a LLM Locally on LM Studio

4 steps

With powerful LLMs available online, like Gemini and ChatGPT, there are still a number of users who choose to use LLMs on their devices. Users often have privacy and security concerns when using the online LLMs, and they feel more secure knowing that sensitive data will not leave their device. Also, running LLMs locally ensures applications remain operational regardless of the status of external services.

In this tutorial, you will download and learn how to use LM Studio. With a user-friendly graphical interface, you will be able to choose your own model to download, and use offline.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

-

Learning Outcomes

By the end of your learning, you will be able to:

  • Download LLMs from the Hugging Face repository
  • Run LLMs locally on your device
  • Adjust model settings to get a desired response

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 4

  • Step 1: Downloading LM Studio

    LM Studio is a program that helps you work with large language models (LLMs), right on your own device. Instead of relying on online services like ChatGPT, LM Studio lets you download, install, and manage powerful LLMs on your computer, giving you more control and keeping your information private.

    Here are some main benefits of using LM Studio for running LLMs:

    1. Easily find and download different LLMs to use.

    2. Run these language models on your own computer, using a graphics processing unit (GPU) for faster processing.

    3. Connect with AnythingLLM for a chatbot feature, allowing you to interact with the program in a more conversational way. 

    Head to https://lmstudio.ai/. Then, download LM Studio for your operating system. For Windows users, note that the file is 435MB.   

    Then, open the downloaded file.

    Next, select a model to download. You can browse for any model available on Hugging Face. Choose a model based on the amount of RAM you have available. The amount of RAM each LLM uses is mentioned in the top right hand corner of the card. For this tutorial, the images and responses you will see are based on the Hermes 2 Pro Mistral 7B model. Wait for the model to complete downloading.

    Next, click on the AI chat icon in the left sidebar. At the top, select the model you just downloaded.

    Then, enter your prompt. Since this is the first time you are interacting with the model, it might be good to find out what it is capable of. Thus, the prompt can be What can you do?

    As you enter your prompt, notice that the number of tokens of your prompt is being counted. Recall in the tutorial LLM Basics Theory that tokens are pieces of words.

    If you are not satisfied with the response you receive, you can click on the Regenerate button to generate another response.

    You can receive the response in plaintext, markdown, and monospace format. This can be toggled by the buttons near the top. 

  • Step 2: Settings

    Click on the gear icon at the top right hand corner will open the settings in the right sidebar. Feel free to adjust any of the settings as you learn about them. 

    Preset

    The first setting you will encounter is the preset. These are a list of pre-made configuration files that determine how the model behaves during inference. For example, if you select the CodeLlama Instruct, the model will behave as a helpful AI coding assistant. To have a rough idea of each preset, select it, and then examine the system prompt.

    The system prompt is what sets the initial context or instructions for the model before it processes any user input.

    Advanced Configuration

    In the advanced configuration menu, there are several settings which may be unfamiliar to you. Heres a description.

    1. Context Length: This determines the number of tokens the model can consider in its context window. A higher context length allows the model to take more previous text into account when generating a response. In the example, it is set to 2048 tokens, but the model can support up to 32768 tokens.
    2. Temperature: Temperature controls the randomness of the model's output. Lower values (closer to 0) make the model's output more deterministic and focused, while higher values (closer to 1) increase the diversity and creativity of the responses. In the example, it is set to 0.8, providing a balance between coherence and creativity.
    3. Tokens to Generate: This setting specifies the number of tokens the model should generate in its response. A value of -1 typically means the model will generate tokens until it reaches a stop condition or the maximum length allowed by the context.

    .

    Inference Parameters

    1. Top K Sampling: Top K sampling limits the model's token choices to the top K most probable next tokens. This helps in controlling the diversity of the output by narrowing down the options to the most likely candidates. In the example, it is set to 40, meaning the model will consider the top 40 most likely tokens at each step.
    2. Repeat Penalty: This parameter penalizes the model for generating repetitive tokens, encouraging it to produce more varied output. A value of 1.1 means there is a slight penalty for repeating the same tokens, promoting diversity in the response.
    3. Min P Sampling: Minimum probability sampling (often called nucleus sampling) only considers the smallest possible set of tokens whose cumulative probability is above a certain threshold. In the example, it is set to 0.05, meaning tokens that together sum up to at least 5% probability will be considered.
    4. Top P Sampling: Similar to Min P sampling, Top P sampling (or nucleus sampling) considers the top P cumulative probability tokens for generating each token in the response. In the example, it is set to 0.95, meaning the model will consider tokens whose cumulative probability is up to 95%.
    5. CPU Threads: This setting specifies the number of CPU threads to use for model inference. Increasing the number of threads can improve performance by allowing parallel processing. In the example, it is set to 4 threads.

    .

    GPU Settings

    If you find your CPU running a little hot while running the prompt, you can offset some of the load to your GPU. Some models allow you to have your GPU do some of the work.

    .

    Prompt Format

    This allows you to customize how the input and output are formatted for the model.

    1. System Message Prefix: This field allows you to add a prefix to the system message. The system message is typically used to set the context or provide initial instructions to the model.
    2. System Message Suffix: This field allows you to add a suffix to the system message.
    3. User Message Prefix: This field allows you to add a prefix to the users input.
    4. Automatically add input prefix to stop strings: When checked, this option ensures that the input prefix is automatically added to any stop strings specified. This helps to maintain consistency in how the model interprets stop strings.
    5. User Message Suffix: This field allows you to add a suffix to the users input.
    6. Stop Strings: Stop strings are specific sequences of characters that, when encountered, will stop the model from generating more tokens. These are used to control where the models output should end.

    .

    Model Initialization

    1. Keep entire model in RAM: When enabled, this option ensures that the entire model is loaded and kept in RAM. This can improve inference speed because the model doesnt need to be paged in and out of memory during use. However, it also means that you need enough RAM to accommodate the entire model.
    2. Prompt eval batch size: This setting determines the batch size for evaluating the prompt. A larger batch size can speed up the processing of multiple inputs by evaluating them in parallel, but it also requires more memory.
    3. Flash Attention: Flash Attention is a technique to accelerate attention mechanisms in transformer models by using optimized memory and compute operations. When enabled, it can improve the efficiency of attention calculations.

    Rotary Position Embedding (RoPE) is a technique used to encode positional information within transformer models, helping them understand the order of tokens in a sequence. The settings here control the parameters for this embedding.

    1. Frequency Scale: This setting scales the frequency of the rotary position embeddings. Adjusting this can change how the model interprets positional information. A scale of 0 means no scaling is applied.
    2. Frequency Base: This setting determines the base frequency for the rotary position embeddings. Similar to the frequency scale, adjusting this can affect how positional information is embedded in the model. A base of 0 means no specific base frequency is applied.
  • Step 3: Tools

    Model Inspector

    The Model Inspector provides detailed information about the current model loaded in LM Studio. The information typically presented includes:

    • name: The name of the model
    • arch: The architecture of the model
    • quant: The quantization type
    • context_length: The maximum context length supported by the model
    • embedding_length: The embedding dimension size
    • num_layers: The number of layers in the model
    • rope: Rotary Position Embedding (RoPE) settings freq_base: The base frequencydimension_count: The dimension count for RoPE
    • freq_base: The base frequency
    • dimension_count: The dimension count for RoPE
    • head_count: The number of attention heads
    • head_count_kv: The number of key-value attention heads
    • parameters: The size of the model parameters

    .

    Context Overflow Policy

    This section defines how the model should handle situations where the generated tokens exceed the context window size. There are three options:

    1. Stop at limit: Stop generating tokens once the context length limit is reached.
    2. Keep the system prompt and the first user message, truncate middle: Keep the system prompt and the first user message intact, but truncate the middle part of the context to fit within the limit.
    3. Maintain a rolling window and truncate past messages: Maintain a rolling window, meaning the most recent messages are kept, and older messages are truncated as new ones are added to stay within the context limit.

    .

    Localization

    This section allows you to set the text direction for the chat interface:

    • Left-to-Right: This is the default setting and is typically used for languages like English, where text is read from left to right.
    • Right-to-Left: This setting is used for languages like Arabic and Hebrew, where text is read from right to left.
  • Step 4: Conclusion

    With that, you now have a program that can help you run LLMs on your device locally. This provides you with a great alternative to the LLMs available online, especially if there are outages, or if you are concerned about privacy.
